                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <locus target="#116v #121r" facs="121 125">Fols. 116v, 121r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    lines of text are written interlinearly
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                    <locus target="#109r" facs="113">f. 109r, line 19</locus>
                    <desc>
                    lines of text are written interlinearly with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e6">
                    <locus target="#78v #118v" facs="083 123">Fols. 78v, 118v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    erasure markings are visible
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e7">
                    <locus target="#116v" facs="121">Fol. 116v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    text has been removed
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e8">
                    <locus target="#1r #2r #2v #6r" facs="005 006 007 010">Folss. 1r, 2r, 2v, 6r, </locus><locus target="#4v #6r" facs="009 010">4v, 6r, </locus><locus target="#16r" facs="020">16r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    The scribe’s chosen aspect ratio for the codex combined with the script size forces the scribe to complete the line of text above the end of the line (e.g, 1r, 2r, 2v, 6r). But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe reduces the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line throughout the codex (e.g, 4v, 6r). The scribe will also wrap the completion of the line onto the next line (e.g, 16r)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                  </list>
